{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500205"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1625"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.29,0.27,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55628"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of palpitations. His medical history is significant for asthma, for which he takes fluticasone with umeclidinium and vilanterol inhaler daily. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An electrocardiogram (ECG) shows an irregularly irregular rhythm. This has been diagnosed as paroxysmal atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate medication for acute management to control his atrial fibrillation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Verapamil","Amiodarone","Metoprolol","Propranolol","Adenosine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of newly diagnosed paroxysmal atrial fibrillation (AF) in a haemodynamically stable patient, the most appropriate acute management is rate control. Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers and beta blockers are considered first-line treatments for this purpose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker, is the most appropriate choice in this scenario. It effectively controls heart rate in AF and is safe to use in patients with asthma, unlike beta blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, while a cardio-selective beta blocker, is still relatively contraindicated in asthma patients. Even cardio-selective beta blockers can potentially cause bronchospasm in sensitive individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-selective beta blocker, is absolutely contraindicated in patients with asthma. Blocking airway \u03b22-receptors can cause severe and potentially fatal bronchoconstriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for acute control of ventricular rate in highly symptomatic AF patients, those with known left ventricular systolic dysfunction, valvular or ischaemic heart disease or in some cases for pharmacological cardioversion. However, it is not first-line for stable patients without cardiovascular history, as in this case of a young otherwise well patient, and with paroxysmal atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenosine\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the management of atrial fibrillation. It has a very short duration of action and is primarily used in the diagnosis and treatment of paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, verapamil is the safest and most appropriate option for acute rate control in this patient with atrial fibrillation and asthma. It provides effective rate control without the risk of exacerbating the patient\u0027s respiratory condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers and beta blockers are first-line acute arrhythmia management for atrial fibrillation in haemodynamically stable patients.","Beta blockers are relatively contraindicated in patients with asthma due to the risk of bronchospasm."],"references":["Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, Bajorek B, Chan KH, Connell C, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. Heart, Lung and Circulation. 2018;27(10):1209-66. Available at: https://www.heartlungcirc.org/article/S1443-9506(18)31778-5/fulltext#secsect0010"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55628"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T20:52:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T20:52:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags"